[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \H9. Your singleton heart is the natural lead against a suit slam — it gives the best shot at a ruff and is the clear choice.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 6\S needing twelve tricks. Count first: six trump tricks in \S, the \HA, the \DK plus dummy's \DA with the long diamonds, and \CA — the trumps, aces, and dummy's strong diamond suit add up to twelve. The slam is cold on top, so the club finesse is unnecessary, and East holds the heart honors you must keep off lead.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West led the \H9, which looks like it could be a singleton — be alert for a ruff. Win the \HA, draw trumps at once to remove any ruff, then cash: six trumps, the \HA, dummy's diamonds for several tricks, and \CA bring twelve. Do NOT take the club finesse — you have your tricks, and a loss would put East in with the hearts. Pull trumps and run your winners to claim.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] Everything you needed was on top once you drew trumps and ran the diamonds — twelve by force, so the finesse had no purpose beyond risking a heart return. You counted, removed the ruff threat, and took the sure road; well played.}
